RACE.RACE_TEXT: WOODBINE RACE 1 5F Inner turf CR: 61. Maiden Claiming Purse 36300. INNER TURF FOR MAIDENS, FILLIES AND MARES THREE YEARS OLD AND UPWARD. Three Year Olds, 119 lbs.; Older, 124 lbs. Claiming Price $15,000, if for $14,000, allowed 1 lb.
RACE.FOOTNOTES: SUMMER SNOW broke sharp to lead from the onset, continued to set fast fractions on the turn, was asking for the wire with an eighth remaining but determinedly hung on for a diminishing margin win at the finish. FRAC TALES tracked the loose frontrunner on the rail, shifted outside for clear run at the quarter pole, was closing with every stride three deep in the stretch but just missed with her late surge at the wire. JO MARCH tracked the pacesetter sitting just outside on the turn, was slowly gaining on the leader between horses through the stretch and could not find another gear late and had to settle for a clear third. LEGAL STEPS travelled in the middle of the pack at the half, kept pace with rivals through the turn and offered some late interest in the final furlong to get up for a small piece of the prize at the finish line. MISS BIKINI travelled on the rail in midfield in the early stages, waited behind a runner inside three eighths from the finish, offered a mild run at the top of the stretch and was outfinished for the minor role in the end. THIS ONE CAN RUN broke inwards to begin, could see most of the field down the back straight, could not improve her position running on the turn and never was in contention. LULU'S LULLABY hit the inside of the gate to start, stalked near the back of the pack with a half mile remaining, could not improve throughout the turn and was not a factor down the lane. INFINITE PASSION stalked near the rear at the half, was a touch headstrong fighting the rider some at the three furlong marker and made little impression driving to the wire. SAKE AND SUSHI was sluggish to get into stride after the break trailing the field down the backstretch, could not get interested running on the turn and made no impact in the stretch run.

RACE.RACE_TEXT: WOODBINE RACE 2 1M Turf CR: 81. Maiden Special Weight Purse 111600. FOR MAIDENS, THREE YEARS OLD AND UPWARD. Three Year Olds, 119 lbs.; Older, 124 lbs.
RACE.FOOTNOTES: SAMMY STONE rated kindly in the middle of the pack on the rail at the half, found a seam in the two path straightening out for the drive, had clear running room at the eighth pole and burst through to get up nearing the wire for the victory. LEGISLATOR had a good position inside tracking the top pair into the turn, shifted off the fence with five sixteenths from home, rallied three deep at the quarter pole to lead at the furlong marker and drifted out late to be caught nearing the wire. TOUCH'N RIDE was unhurried in the beginning to be near the rear down the backside, started to commence a run three wide around runners at the half, shifted out to the five path to loom the threat turning for home and was pushed out in the final eighth to capture third money. DIRECT DRIVE had a narrow lead running throughout the turn, was headed outside at the furlong marker, could not find more to repel challengers and faded late settling for a small share in the end. COHERENCE was allowed to settle on the rail trailing the field down the backstretch, took closer order to the pack to be involved at the top of the lane and passed tired runners finishing up on the fence down the stretch. WICKED DJANGO tracked three deep outside horses behind the top two in the beginning, was nudged on between foes to offer a bid three furlongs from home, was in the hunt at the top of the lane running in the four path and stalled in mid stretch. FIGHTING IRISH stalked in mid field two deep at the half mile marker, angled out widest for the stretch drive behind runners in the five path and levelled out in the final eighth. HANK OLLIE was content to sit just outside off the pacesetter at the half, could not quicken with horses at the three furlong marker, was shuffled back through the turn and was not a factor in the stretch run. FINN'S MOMENT refused at the start and walked off. STEWARDS INQUIRY REGARDING #8 FINN'S MOMENT AT THE BREAK WAS DEEMED TO HAVE RECIEVED A FAIR START. ALSO, STEWARDS GENERAL REVIEW REGARDING #5 LEGISLATOR AND #7 TOUCH N" RIDE NEARING THE FINISH LINE RESULTED IN NO CHANGE

RACE.FOOTNOTES: QUEEN JUDITH was relaxed going down the backstretch trailing the field, advanced smartly on the rail with five sixteenths from the line, put in the winning move splitting runners quickly in mid stretch to lead by the furlong pole and was kept to the task to hold safe for the victory. PEMBERLEY travelled near the back of the pack in the beginning stages of the race, angled outside in the seven path to be widest for the drive to the finish, began to pick up runners in mid stretch to loom boldly at the eighth pole but could not gain enough late to threaten the winner. VIVID VIXEN stalked near the rear down the backside, waited behind runners at the top of the lane found a seam on the rail three sixteenths from the wire and slipped up the fence to capture third money in the end. WITCH HAZEL was in tight quarters to begin, tracked in the second flight outside with four furlongs to run, was in the mix up front in the five path two furlongs from the finish and was one paced in deep stretch. TWIRLING CAT had a good position watching the top two leaders five furlongs from the wire, was asked turning for home, lost path nearing the eighth pole and offered little in the stretch run under left handed urging late. PIONEER'S EDGE was nestled on the rail behind the top duo at the five furlong pole, waited patiently inside throughout the turn, shifted three wide at quarter marker and gave way with runners on either side in the final furlong. COURTLY RO settled near the rear three deep outside foes at the half mile marker, was ridden to go on six wide at the top of the lane and could not get into contention driving to the wire. LADY URUS broke out to begin, took the field into the turn, continued to set the pace to open up mildly at the top of the stretch, was swallowed up by runners at the eighth pole and emptied out in the late stages of the race. DIOSA CATRINA broke inwards at the start, prompted the early pace scenario outside, was ridden to keep position at the five sixteenths marker and backed away with runners on either side in upper stretch.

RACE.FOOTNOTES: LUCKY SCORE was bumped on the break, steadied mildly soon after the start to trail on the fence down the back straight, found clear run four deep at the top of the lane, shifted inwards under a drive three sixteenths from the wire and gamely wore down his rivals late to edge away for the victory crossing the line. OCEANIC stumbled on the start, stalked outside at the back with a half mile to go, still could see the field running behind horses in the six path in upper stretch, determinedly split rivals nearing the sixteenth pole and battled gamely to the finish but could not get the win in a hard fought gutsy effort. ONE TIMER engaged three wide outside horses under a lively early pace, took command in the six path in upper stretch, switched back to the outside lead at the sixteenth pole, lost some momentum and finished evenly nearing the wire. OLD CHESTNUT brushed the inside rival on the break, had a good position on the fence watching the top three battle running on the turn, shifted outside seven wide for the stretch drive having clear run, looked to be the winner closing strongly at the eighth pole but stalled outside in deep stretch. SOUPER DORMY stalked between challengers near the back in the early going, rallied widest in lane eight at the top of the stretch to be in the mix for a piece of the prize but could not find another gear in the final furlong to pose a threat in the late stages. OUTLAW KID was brushed outside to start, prompted the pace between runners down the backside, bid for the lead with runners on either side turning for home and yielded at the furlong marker. MASSETO (GB) was bumped on the start, settled on the rail near the rear in the early going, offered a slight turn of foot entering the stretch three wide, lost its path inside the three sixteenths pole and had no rally to offer in the late running. STRIKER stalked four deep outside horses near the back of the pack throughout the turn, could see the field in last four wide two furlongs from home and passed the tiring early frontrunner in deep stretch. CADAMOSTO (IRE) led the field on the fence down the backstretch, was hounded outside by the couple of runners while setting strong fractions through the turn, a quarter mile from home was collared by the other speed rivals contesting the pace, retreated in mid stretch and was not persevered with on the rail to the finish.

RACE.FOOTNOTES: TYSON broke outwardly just a bit bumping lightly with a rival, exchanged light contact with an inside foe heading into the first turn, was in a bit tight between and behind runners into that bend, raced three to five wide mid-pack, angled out seven wide leaving the far turn to advance past foes, took aim on the leader, struck the front a sixteenth out and edged clear while running on the wrong lead. TREASON was bumped after the start, rated mid-division off the pace caught four to six wide through the first turn, edged closer on the far turn outside foes five wide striking the lead near the three-sixteenths, was overtaken coming to the sixteenth pole but well clear of the rest. GASTON broke inwardly, bumped with a rival lightly and was in a bit tight heading to the first turn racing two to three wide between runners on that bend, shifted out five wide turning for home before being guided out a bit further, kept on late to get up for third. WAR BOMBER (IRE) came out several paths after the start and with the lead, set the pace in the three path into the first turn, was headed and pressured past the three-quarter marker, vied inside retaking the lead at the half, could not kick on with the top pair and drifted out gradually through the lane, lost show late. RACE.FOOTNOTES: FEV ROVER (IRE) was patiently handled galloping along four deep down the backstretch trailing the pack into the turn, was in no rush in last watching the race unfold while in range of the field with three furlongs to go, continued to be unhurried sitting behind a wall of runners in upper stretch, a path opened up five wide with three sixteenths to go, quickly burst through when asked to get the lead and drew away comfortably nearing the wire. MOIRA was squeezed between runners on the start to trail in the early going, was then hustled down the backside to get early position sitting behind the leaders with five eighths to go, shifted off the tiring pacesetter inside three furlongs from home, had clear run splitting foes at the furlong pole and finished well to best the rest at the wire. MILLIE GIRL tracked the top two between horses in the second flight, was urged on the turn keeping up with other rivals, fought on stubbornly in the six path when surrounded by runners never giving in and finished up late to capture third money in a gritty stretch effort. DEVIL'S BIT broke inwards to begin, settled three deep between foes near the rear at the half, started to rally around horses three wide at the three eighths marker, bid for the front five wide straightening out for the drive and stalled with an eighth remaining to hold for a minor role. EMINENT VICTOR was unhurried down the backstretch shifting inwards to the rail with three quarters remaining, stalked in the third flight inside through the turn while on hold behind horses, was coaxed for more run shifting out to be six wide entering the lane and was one paced in deep stretch. SCOTISH STAR (ARG) broke out on the start, pressured the frontrunner outside through the turn, had a slim lead between foes three eighths from the finish, was headed outside by the closers two furlongs from home, battled on for another furlong and faded on the fence in the final sixteenth. PURRFECT was situated near the back of the pack four deep outside runners at the half, could not make any gain outside challengers running through the turn, angled out widest in the seven path for the stretch drive and could no be a presence running to the wire. SWEET ENOUGH (GB) sat outside watching the contesting duo into the turn, began to inch closer to the front runners at the three furlong marker, contested for the lead four wide with runners on either side two furlongs from the wire, shortened stride in mid stretch and tired in the late stages. SISTER LOU ANN led the field on the rail down the backside, narrowly held on to the lead in the early part of the turn, was collared outside three furlongs from the wire, had nothing left to give inside at the top of the lane and retreated in mid stretch.

RACE.FOOTNOTES: GRANDE BELLA was among and between early leaders then moved to the fore and clear by the five-eighths, extended the margin turning into upper stretch racing just off the inside, was weakening late, fought on desperately under stout urging and lasted. P. S. RISING STAR was forwardly-positioned stalking, went three to four wide on the turn, drifted out in late stretch while gaining, surged but missed. HARD ROCK WARRIOR switched off the rail in the early going under mild encouragement to keep pace with the field, lacked room in behind tiring rivals past the five-sixteenths, shifted out three deep at that juncture, came out further in upper stretch and finished well to secure show honors. ROYAL CHROME settled off the pace, advanced outside shifting from four to six wide on the turn, drifted in a bit in the stretch and evened out. SILENT CREEK broke outwardly just a bit, steadied two times when in tight coming near the five-eighths, shifted in soon after, advanced up the rail on the turn, came out a bit passing the five-sixteenths, sought room between foes in upper stretch, split at the furlong marker and ran on. BABA'S GIRL was forwardly-positioned into the turn, went four to five on that bend outside runners, asked for more turning for home, lacked the needed late kick. CANDY WINE was among the early leaders racing inside, saved ground in pursuit through the turn, faded in the stretch. SOME LIKE IT HOT was forwardly-positioned between runners chasing two to three wide on the turn, dropped back and faded. IVICTORY dwelt at the start then veered out when leaving the stalls spotting the field about six or seven lengths, was hard-ridden at that juncture but lost yet more ground to the field, saved ground on the turn, was never a threat. BLUEBERRY DOLL raced off the pace, was between foes three to four wide on the turn and never near enough to threaten.
